<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-744-794  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 744 794.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Personal Computing  Oct 1989 v13 n10 p234(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The computing industry at age thirtysomething. (Commentary)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shaffer, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer industry is approximately thirty years old, andcomputers have become central to businesses.andP;  Gradually, computerswill become a more basic part of our economy.andP;  However, ascomputers become increasingly important to the economy, theeconomy becomes more important to computers.andP;  Steady growth in thecomputer industry is gone, and now Americans realize thatmicrocomputers sell just like other capital goods, with salesrising and falling according to factors such as the economicclimate.andP;  Investors are still interested in new computercompanies, especially software companies, companies that makecommunications products for distributed computing, and thosebuilding on the basic concept of the microcomputer itself.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryMicrocomputersEconomics of ComputingMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>